{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659694","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659694"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:14:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:14:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20887"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20887"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13762"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96846"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13762","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13762"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20887"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79461"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"10763"},{"type":"tags","id":"11801"},{"type":"tags","id":"12712"},{"type":"tags","id":"12713"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"},{"type":"tags","id":"12796"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33158"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33162"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96846"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EFragile X syndrome is the most common inherited cause of intellectual disability. The condition demonstrates genetic anticipation, with increasing severity in successive generations.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following most accurately describes the molecular mechanism underlying Fragile X syndrome?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Overexpression of FMR1 gene causing excessive protein synthesis","Complete deletion of the FMR1 gene from the X chromosome","Hypermethylation of the FMR1 promoter causing gene silencing","Point mutation in the FMR1 gene creating a non-functional protein","Inversion of the FMR1 gene disrupting its reading frame"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFragile X syndrome results from \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypermethylation of the FMR1 promoter causing gene silencing\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs when CGG trinucleotide repeats in the 5\u0027 untranslated region of the FMR1 gene expand beyond approximately 200 repeats. This expansion triggers DNA methylation of the promoter region, preventing transcription and resulting in absence of the Fragile X Mental Retardation Protein (FMRP).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOverexpression of FMR1 gene causing excessive protein synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E - Fragile X syndrome involves reduced or absent FMRP, not increased production\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete deletion of the FMR1 gene from the X chromosome\u003C/strong\u003E - The gene remains physically present but is transcriptionally silenced\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPoint mutation in the FMR1 gene creating a non-functional protein\u003C/strong\u003E - The primary mechanism is transcriptional silencing rather than production of altered protein\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInversion of the FMR1 gene disrupting its reading frame\u003C/strong\u003E - The condition results from trinucleotide expansion and methylation, not chromosomal rearrangements\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFMRP functions as an RNA-binding protein that regulates translation at synapses. Its absence leads to dysregulated protein synthesis at neuronal synapses, impairing synaptic plasticity and contributing to the cognitive and behavioral features of Fragile X syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Fragile X syndrome is caused by CGG trinucleotide repeat expansion in the FMR1 gene, with full mutations having over 200 repeats.","The expanded CGG repeats lead to DNA methylation of the FMR1 promoter region, resulting in transcriptional silencing and absence of FMRP.","FMRP normally regulates protein synthesis at neuronal synapses, and its absence disrupts synaptic development and function."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 5, Genetic Disorders; p. 174-177"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79461"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20887"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79461","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79461"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-03T08:37:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-03T08:39:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13762"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96846"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10763"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Genetic disorders","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-11-21T13:05:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T13:05:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11801","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11801"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Single-gene disorders with nonclassic inheritance","synon